Different Models

Quadratic Model

\[ Y_i =\underbrace{ \overbrace{\quad \beta_0 + \beta_1X_i + \beta_2X_i^2}^{\text{Quadratic Model}}}_{E\{Y_i\}}\quad + \epsilon_i \]

## Simulating Data from a Regression Model
  ## This R-chunk is meant to be played in your R Console.
  ## It allows you to explore how the various elements
  ## of the regression model combine together to "create"
  ## data and then use the data to "re-create" the line.

  set.seed(101) #Allows us to always get the same "random" sample
                #Change to a new number to get a new sample

  n <- 30 #set the sample size

  X_i <- runif(n, -45, 45) 
    #Gives n random values from a uniform distribution between 15 to 45.

  beta0 <- 3 #Our choice for the y-intercept. 

  beta1 <- 1.8 #Our choice for the slope. 
  
  beta2 <- 3

  sigma <- 250 #Our choice for the std. deviation of the error terms.


  epsilon_i <- rnorm(n, 0, sigma) 
    #Gives n random values from a normal distribution with mean = 0, st. dev. = sigma.

  Y_i <- beta0 + beta1*X_i + beta2*X_i^2 + epsilon_i 
    #Create Y using the normal error regression model

  fabData <- data.frame(y=Y_i, x=X_i) 
    #Store the data as data

  

  #In the real world, we begin with data (like fabData) and try to recover the model that 
  # (we assume) was used to created it.

  fab.lm <- lm(y ~ x + I(x^2) , data=fabData) #Fit an estimated regression model to the fabData.

  pander(summary(fab.lm)) #Summarize your model.
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) -123.1 65.55 -1.878 0.07128
x 1.524 1.926 0.7913 0.4357
I(x^2) 3.125 0.08038 38.87 3.053e-25
Fitting linear model: y ~ x + I(x^2)
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
30 251.6 0.9825 0.9812 
  plot(y ~ x, data=fabData) #Plot the data.
  
  b <- coef(fab.lm)

  curve(b[1] + b[2]*x + b[3]*x^2, add = T, lty = 1) #Add the estimated regression line to your plot.
  curve(beta0 + beta1*x + beta2*x^2, add = T, lty = 2)



  # Now for something you can't do in real life... but since we created the data...
    #Add the true regression line to your plot using a dashed line (lty=2). 

  legend("topleft", legend = c("True Line", "Estimated Line"), lty=c(2,1), bty="n") 

    #Add a legend to your plot specifying which line is which.

Real Data Example (Crime Dataset)

dat <- Crime

crime.lm <- lm(crmrte ~ wfed + I(wfed^2), data = Crime)

pander(summary(crime.lm))
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 0.09409 0.01994 4.719 2.919e-06
wfed -0.0004423 9.836e-05 -4.497 8.215e-06
I(wfed^2) 6.95e-07 1.197e-07 5.804 1.027e-08
Fitting linear model: crmrte ~ wfed + I(wfed^2)
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
630 0.0159 0.2324 0.2299 
b <- coef(crime.lm)

r2 <- summary(crime.lm)$r.squared

dat %>% 
 ggplot +
  geom_point(aes(x = wfed, y = crmrte), color = "darksalmon", alpha = .5) +
  stat_function(fun = function(x) (b[1]) + b[2]*x + b[3]*x^2, color = "steelblue3", lwd = 1.5) +
  annotate("text", label = paste0("R^2 == ", r2), color = "steelblue3", parse = T, x = 550, y = .15) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = "bold")) +
  labs(x = "Weekly Federal Pay", y = "Crimes Commited Per Person", title = "As Federal Wages Increases Crime Also Increases")

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(crime.lm, which = 1:2)

Cubic Model

\[ Y_i =\underbrace{ \overbrace{\quad \beta_0 + \beta_1X_i + \beta_2X_i^2 + \beta_3 X_i^3}^{\text{Quadratic Model}}}_{E\{Y_i\}}\quad + \epsilon_i \]

## Simulating Data from a Regression Model
  ## This R-chunk is meant to be played in your R Console.
  ## It allows you to explore how the various elements
  ## of the regression model combine together to "create"
  ## data and then use the data to "re-create" the line.

  set.seed(101) #Allows us to always get the same "random" sample
                #Change to a new number to get a new sample

  n <- 30 #set the sample size

  X_i <- runif(n, -45, 45) 
    #Gives n random values from a uniform distribution between 15 to 45.

  beta0 <- 3 #Our choice for the y-intercept. 

  beta1 <- 1.8 #Our choice for the slope. 
  
  beta2 <- 3
  
  beta3 <- 2.2

  sigma <- 50000 #Our choice for the std. deviation of the error terms.


  epsilon_i <- rnorm(n, 0, sigma) 
    #Gives n random values from a normal distribution with mean = 0, st. dev. = sigma.

  Y_i <- beta0 + beta1*X_i + beta2*X_i^2 + beta3*X_i^3 + epsilon_i 
    #Create Y using the normal error regression model

  fabData <- data.frame(y=Y_i, x=X_i) 
    #Store the data as data

  

  #In the real world, we begin with data (like fabData) and try to recover the model that 
  # (we assume) was used to created it.

  fab.lm <- lm(y ~ x + I(x^2) + I(x^3) , data=fabData) #Fit an estimated regression model to the fabData.

  pander(summary(fab.lm)) #Summarize your model.

  plot(y ~ x, data=fabData) #Plot the data.
  
  b <- coef(fab.lm)

  curve(b[1] + b[2]*x + b[3]*x^2 + b[4]*x^3, add = T, lty = 1) #Add the estimated regression line to your plot.
  curve(beta0 + beta1*x + beta2*x^2 + beta3*x^3, add = T, lty = 2)



  # Now for something you can't do in real life... but since we created the data...

Two-Lines Model

\[ Y_i = \underbrace{\overbrace{\quad \quad\beta_0 + \beta_1X_{1i} + \beta_2X_{2i} + \beta_3X_{1i}X_{2i}}^{\quad\quad\text{ Two-Lines Model}}}_{\quad \quad E\{Y_i\}} + \epsilon_i \]

\[ \ X_{2i} = \begin{cases} 1, \quad \text{Group A} \\ 0, \quad \text{Group B} \end{cases} \ \]

## Simulating Data from a Regression Model
  ## This R-chunk is meant to be played in your R Console.
  ## It allows you to explore how the various elements
  ## of the regression model combine together to "create"
  ## data and then use the data to "re-create" the line.

  set.seed(101) #Allows us to always get the same "random" sample
                #Change to a new number to get a new sample

  n <- 30 #set the sample size

  X_i1 <- runif(n, 0, 45) 
    #Gives n random values from a uniform distribution between 15 to 45.
  X_i2 <- sample(c(0,1), n ,replace = TRUE)
  
  beta0 <- 3 #Our choice for the y-intercept. 

  beta1 <- 1.8 #Our choice for the slope. 
  
  beta2 <- 3
  
  beta3 <- 2.2

  sigma <- 50 #Our choice for the std. deviation of the error terms.


  epsilon_i <- rnorm(n, 0, sigma) 
    #Gives n random values from a normal distribution with mean = 0, st. dev. = sigma.

  Y_i <- beta0 + beta1*X_i1 + beta2*X_i2 + beta3*X_i1*X_i2 + epsilon_i 
    #Create Y using the normal error regression model

  fabData <- data.frame(y=Y_i, x1 = X_i1, x2 = X_i2) 
    #Store the data as data
  

  #In the real world, we begin with data (like fabData) and try to recover the model that 
  # (we assume) was used to created it.

  fab.lm <- lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x1:x2 , data = fabData) #Fit an estimated regression model to the fabData.

  pander(summary(fab.lm)) #Summarize your model.
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) -28.86 30.46 -0.9475 0.3521
x1 2.61 0.9927 2.629 0.01418
x2 91.03 42.4 2.147 0.04132
x1:x2 -1.769 1.695 -1.044 0.3062
Fitting linear model: y ~ x1 + x2 + x1:x2
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
30 48.82 0.2951 0.2137 
  plot(y ~ x1, data = fabData, col = as.factor(x2)) #Plot the data.
  
  b <- coef(fab.lm)

  curve(b[1] + b[2]*x, add = T, col = "black") #Add the estimated regression line to your plot.
  #abline(beta0,beta1, lty = 2)
  
  
  curve(b[1] + b[3] + (b[2] + b[4])*x, add  = T, col = "red", lty = 1) 
  
  
  # Now for something you can't do in real life... but since we created the data...

    #Add the true regression line to your plot using a dashed line (lty=2). 

  legend("topleft", legend=c("Changed Line", "Base Line"), lty=c(2,1), bty="n", col = c("red", "black")) 

    #Add a legend to your plot specifying which line is which.

Real Data Example (Orange Dataset)

dat2 <- channing


chan.lm <- lm(exit ~ entry + factor(cens) + entry:factor(cens), data = dat2)

pander(summary(chan.lm))
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 302.4 37.97 7.963 1.338e-14
entry 0.7595 0.04244 17.9 1.082e-54
factor(cens)1 -196.8 59.19 -3.325 0.0009556
entry:factor(cens)1 0.1998 0.06467 3.089 0.002132
Fitting linear model: exit ~ entry + factor(cens) + entry:factor(cens)
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
462 46.17 0.6108 0.6082 
b2 <- coef(chan.lm)

r2 <- summary(chan.lm)$r.squared

dat2 %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x = entry, y = exit, color = factor(cens)), alpha = .5) +
  stat_function(fun = function(x) b2[1] + b2[2]*x, color = "steelblue1", lwd = 1.3, lty = 1) +
  stat_function(fun = function(x) (b2[1] + b2[3])  + (b2[2] + b[4])*x, color = "red")
